Flat world's fragility
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman as such says. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
The world is getting smaller.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide easy protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States are both facing the challenge of global competition.
Western consumers who call local companies may be speaking to employees who are actually in India.
Doubters have pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As some have said, the world is not flat but "bumpy".
As some have said, the world's economic activities are depicted on a contour map showing prosperous peaks and impoverished valleys.
The world is getting smaller than ever before.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have far more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Vancouver and Seattle are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with Toronto, which is farther away, far exceeds that with neighboring Seattle.
Despite such criticism, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence among different continents, as ancient as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, and the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, with a faster pace of development and a deeper level of integration.
After the Atlantic telegraph cable was completed in 1868, Europeans and Americans could communicate with each other in as little as a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes depicted British people living in London ordering goods by telephone from all over the world and then waiting at home for delivery in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British people belonged to the exception of being wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similar to this, 20 years ago, there was instant global communication, but it was beyond the financial reach of the vast majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet cafe and acquire capabilities that were once the exclusive domain of governments, multinational corporations, and a select few individuals or organizations with large budgets.
The sharp decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of internet users were still concentrated in the United States.
While today, the United States' internet users account for less than a quarter of the world's total.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who possess information has reached a record high in human history.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were once exclusively in the hands of governments.
National states as major players in the world's politics will not undergo a change in status for the time being, but they must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of participants, including institutions like the Oxford Famine Relief Committee, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Similar to this, 20 years ago, there was instant global communication, but it was beyond the financial reach of the vast majority of people.
In the years following World War I, global economic interdependence had reached a high level, but over the next 30 years, countries' economic reliance on one another continued to decline.
Until 1970, the global economy had recovered to the level of integration it had once reached, and it was still heavily separated by the Iron Curtain at the time.
The First World War served as the catalyst for this reversal, as people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization during the two World Wars and the Cold War.
This reflects more profound issues of domestic inequality caused by 19th-century economic development.
Political systems failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideological extremes – Fascism and Communism – that fragmented the world and nation-states.
After the Second World War, Western welfare states provided a safety net for those affected by economic change, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today bears a striking resemblance to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic disparities, ceaselessly developing toward nationalism, challenging dominant powers, and ultimately triggering a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, were the economies of Britain and Germany not similarly intertwined before 1914?
But such reasoning is incomplete.
After Germany's industrial production surpassed that of Britain in the 20th century.
However, even if China's economy continues to maintain its current high growth rate, it is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States in at least 20 years.
The potential threat to the flat world is more likely to come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, the number of Americans killed in a surprise attack by a non-state network far exceeded the number of Americans killed in the 1941 Japanese government's Pearl Harbor attack.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would be turned upside down.
At that time, it would become increasingly difficult for people and goods to cross national borders.
If such forces were to disrupt oil production in the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen protectionist forces.
Technology and policy are the two main drivers of globalization.
To date, policies have further solidified the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken a leading role in driving policies aimed at removing obstacles.
But the events described above could reverse this policy.
Some globalization critics might welcome such a reversal.
But such a reversal, as we saw after 1914, will lead to the worst-case scenario in two fields: the reversal of the economic globalization trend driven by the spread of technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization will be further solidified, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that's the case, the flat world will become a desert.
